Networks - day 4

2023-03-14

Clustering

The Stochastic Topic Blocl model

To use the SBM model, we need to install the blockmodel package.

#install.packages('blockmodels')
library(blockmodels)

Lets start by simulating a SBM network:

npc <- 30 # nodes per class
Q <- 3 # groups
n <- npc * Q # nodes
Z <- diag(Q) %x% matrix(1,npc,1)
P <- rbind(c(0.2,0.01,0.01),
           c(0.02,0.15,0.01),
           c(0.01,0.02,0.25))
M <- 1*(matrix(runif(n*n),n,n) < Z %*% P %*% t(Z))
image(M)

library(sna)

gplot(M)

Once the network is generated according to the model, we can ask SBM to recover the clusters.

my_model <- BM_bernoulli("SBM",M,
                         explore_min = 1,
                         explore_max = 10)
my_model$estimate()

Afterward, it is possible to visualize the meta-network:

pi = my_model$model_parameters[[3]]$pi
gplot(pi,vertex.col=1:3,
      diag=TRUE,
      usecurve=TRUE,
      edge.lwd=100*pi,
      loop.cex = 3)

Exercise: simulate a network with 3 communities and a group of a few stars.

rho = c(30,30,30,3) / 93
Z = t(rmultinom(100,1,rho))
n = 100
P <- rbind(c(0.2,0,0,0.2),
           c(0,0.15,0,0.2),
           c(0,0,0.25,0.2),
           c(0,0,0,0.01))
M <- 1*(matrix(runif(n*n),n,n) < Z %*% P %*% t(Z))
image(M)

library(sna)
gplot(M,edge.col='grey',vertex.col=max.col(Z))
